To represent a chess board state in LaTeX using FEN notation, you can use the `skak` and `xskak` packages, which are designed for typesetting chess games. Here is an example of a LaTeX code that includes all the required commands and packages.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{xskak}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\newchessgame
\setchessboard{showmover=false}

% Here, replace the FEN string with your own
\fenboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}

\chessboard

\end{document}
```

The `xskak` package is a extension of the `skak` package and provides additional commands to typeset chess games. The `chessboard` package provides the command to draw the board.

Remember to replace the FEN string in the `\fenboard` command with your own FEN string. 

The 'w' in the FEN string indicates it's white's move, 'KQkq' refers to the castling availability (K = white can castle kingside, Q = white can castle queenside, k = black can castle kingside, q = black can castle queenside), '-' indicates no square is available for en passant, and '0 1' is the halfmove clock and fullmove number respectively. 

Please ensure to compile the document with PDFLaTeX, as the `skak` package uses PostScript for drawing, which is not supported by all LaTeX compilers.

